Greetings to Libyan Leader 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 1 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, Sunday sent a message of greetings to Moammer El Gaddafi, leader of the Great September First Revolution of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, on the occasion of the 34th anniversary of the revolution in Libya.
 The message extended warmest congratulations to the leader and, through him, to the leadership and people of Libya. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The message said the Libyan people were working hard to defend the national dignity and the sovereignty of the country and build a free and prosperous new society under his guidance. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Believing that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would grow stronger in the future, it wished him good health and happiness.

Korean Film Week Opens in Russia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 1 (KCNA) -- A Korean film week was opened with due ceremony at the hall of the Russian Filmmakers Union in Moscow on Aug. 27 to mark the 55th anniversary of the DPRK.
 The first vice-chairman of the union in his speech at the inaugural ceremony extended warmest congratulations to all the Korean people on the occasion of the 55th anniversary of the DPRK, adding that it was very pleased to open the Korean film week on the occasion. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Saying that Russia and the DPRK have conducted brisk contact and cooperation in the field of cinematic art as in other fields, he noted that the peoples of the two countries have promoted the bilateral understanding and deepened the feelings of traditional friendship through cultural interaction. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said that the heroic spirit and innovative successes of the Korean people please their Russian friends. He wished the Korean people greater success in their drive to build a great prosperous powerful nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants enjoyed film "From Spring to Summer."

Rodong Sinmun on DPRK's Nuclear Deterrent 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 1 (KCNA) -- The U.S. bellicose forces these days are throwing together the balderdash that the DPRK's nuclear deterrent is intended to "threaten and blackmail" somebody and to be sold to other countries and it may strike U.S. cities when it finds its way into the hands of terrorists.
 Refuting this, Rodong Sinmun Monday in a signed commentary says that all this is a nonsense and the DPRK's nuclear deterrent force is aimed at coping with the U.S. preemptive nuclear attack on and armed invasion of the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The commentary goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Our nuclear deterrent which embodies the principle of self-reliant defense based on the Juche idea is of defensive nature. In other word, it is, to all intents and purposes, a means of defending sovereignty. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is utterly groundless that our nuclear deterrent poses "threat" to somebody. And it is the height of folly to argue that our nuclear deterrent is a "threat" to the U.S. and nobody would believe this. It is, indeed, a brigandish logic that only our nuclear deterrent is "dangerous" while U.S. nuclear weapons raise no problem on the Korean peninsula. Our nuclear deterrent for defending the sovereignty of the country can never be a threat to anyone. Unless anyone provokes the DPRK, its nuclear deterrent will remain unused. There is no need for a country not hostile but friendly to the DPRK to worry about its nuclear deterrent. The defensive nature and mission of our nuclear deterrent will remain unchanged.
